ls: Lists files and directories in the current directory.
Example: ls -l (detailed list with permissions).

cd: Changes the current directory.
Example: cd /home/user/Documents.

pwd: Prints the current working directory.

mkdir: Creates a new directory.
Example: mkdir new_folder.

rmdir: Deletes an empty directory.
Example: rmdir old_folder.

touch: Creates an empty file or updates its timestamp.
Example: touch new_file.txt.

cat: Displays the contents of a file.
Example: cat file.txt.

more: Paginates the file for easier viewing.
Example: more long_file.txt.

less: Similar to more, but allows backward navigation.
Example: less long_file.txt.

head: Displays the first few lines of a file.
Example: head -n 10 file.txt (first 10 lines).

tail: Displays the last few lines of a file.
Example: tail -n 10 file.txt (last 10 lines).

cp: Copies files or directories.
Example: cp file.txt /destination.

mv: Moves or renames files and directories.
Example: mv oldname.txt newname.txt.

rm: Deletes files or directories.
Example: rm file.txt.

chmod: Changes file or directory permissions.
Example: chmod 755 file.sh.

chown: Changes file ownership.
Example: chown user:group file.txt.

stat: Displays detailed information about a file.
Example: stat file.txt.

find: Searches for files and directories.
Example: find /home -name "file.txt".

locate: Finds files using a pre-built database (faster than find).
Example: locate file.txt.

grep: Searches for text within files.
Example: grep "keyword" file.txt.

tar: Archives files and directories.
Example: tar -cvf archive.tar files.

gzip: Compresses files.
Example: gzip file.txt.

unzip: Extracts files from a .zip archive.
Example: unzip archive.zip.

du: Checks the disk usage of a file or directory.
Example: du -h file.txt.

df: Checks available disk space.
Example: df -h.